g.aria-label: Mr.Spock took a very powerful, cylindrical permanent magnet to outer space and performed the following two experiments:

A. He spins the magnet about the magnet's North-South axis at an angular velocity w.
B. He spins the magnet about an axis, which makes a non-zero angle 0 with the magnet's North-South axis, at an angular velocity .
How does the angular velocity of the magnet change with time in experiment A?

(a) decreases with time.
(b) remains the same
(c) increases with time.
(d) increases then decreases with time
In both the cases, he moves away from the magnet after spinning it and observes it from a distance. Consider the magnet to be a dipole. Assume zero gravity and zero air resistance.
How does the angular velocity of the magnet change with time in experiment B?

The magnet can lose energy only via the electromagnetic fields.
Let the Z-axis be along the North-South direction The magnet is a cylinder.Hence the magnetic field generated by it will be symmetric with respect to . So, rotating the magnet along the North-South axis wouldn't change the magnetic field at any point. Hence, there are is no radiation and the magnet does not lose energy. Hence, rotation is unaffected.
In experiment B, the rotation is along an arbitrary axis not passing through the North-South axis. Hence, magnetic field would change with time. This changing magnetic field would cause energy to be transported out of the system. Hence, the system loses energy and slows down.
